le":"1503–Deceased","1505–Female":"1505–Deceased","16 February 1562":"16 February 1562","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","Abt 1527":"about 1527","2 April 1562":"2 April 1562","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1645":"1645","1545":"1545","1565":"1565","1662":"1662","1574":"1574","1562":"1562","1540":"1540","about 1565":"about 1565","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","of Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Chudleigh, Teignbridge, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chudleigh, Devon, England","Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, England","England":"England","Chudleigh,Devon,England":"Chudleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bennett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the medieval personal name   Benedict  , from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. In the 12th century the Latin form of the name is found in England alongside versions derived from the Old French form <i>Beneit</i>, <i>Benoit</i>, which was common among the Normans. The surname has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Bernhard  .","Altered form of French   Benet   or   Bennet   or of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bennet","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  .","French: derivative of   Benne  ."]},{"name":"Bennitt","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennetts","meanings":["English (Cornwall): variant of   Bennett  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Dittus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Fritz, Kurt, Otto, Reinhold.","German: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Benedictus</i> (see   Bennett  )."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bennette","meanings":["English (Cornwall): altered form of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Benett","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennight","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Bene(i)t</i> + <i>-son</i>. See   Bennett   and compare   Benson  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":4,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":13,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":24,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Bennett was born in 1545, in Chudleigh, Devon, England, her father, William Bennett, was 43 and her mother, Mrs. William Bennett, was 41. She married John Radford II on 2 April 1562, in Chudleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1570, in her hometown, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1545–1570":"1545–1570","1540–1574":"1540–1574","1560–1645":"1560–1645","1562–Male":"1562–Surnud","1565–Female":"1